## 0) First time after creating or changing unit files

```bash
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable vm-control.service
sudo systemctl enable pgvm-postgres.service
```

If you only change `/run/pgvm/*.env`, you do **not** need `daemon-reload`.

---

## 1) Start PostgreSQL

Write the runtime cluster info first.

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /run/pgvm

sudo tee /run/pgvm/cluster.env >/dev/null <<'EOF'
PGMAJOR=16
PG_BIN_DIR=/usr/pgsql-16/bin
PGDATA=/data/local/mydb/16/data
PGPORT=5432
PGCLUSTER_NAME=mydb
PGOPTS=
EOF
```

Then start:

```bash
sudo systemctl start pgvm-postgres.service
```

Check status:

```bash
sudo systemctl status pgvm-postgres.service
```

See logs:

```bash
sudo journalctl -u pgvm-postgres.service -f
```

---

## 2) Stop PostgreSQL with defaults

If you do nothing, your stop wrapper should default to:

* `PG_STOP_MODE=fast`
* `PG_STOP_TIMEOUT=90`

So just do:

```bash
sudo systemctl stop pgvm-postgres.service
```

